// Conformance case: Stable "`unsafe` blocks" (STABILITY.md § Feature
// Stability › Stable) — "required wrapper for volatile MMIO
// intrinsics; the `unsafe { ... }` syntax and the compile-time gate
// ... are stable." This case pins that an `unsafe { ... }` block is
// not just a syntactic no-op wrapper: ordinary statements inside it
// (assignment, `println`) execute exactly as they would outside it.
// It does not call `volatile_read_*`/`volatile_write_*` against a real
// address — see `resilient/examples/unsafe_block_smoke.rz`, which pins
// that those intrinsics are *reachable* inside `unsafe` (no address to
// round-trip against without a real or emulated peripheral).
//
// KNOWN GAP (#4024): `--vm` currently drops the entire block body and
// treats `unsafe { ... }` as if it evaluated to `0`, so this case is
// listed in `VM_BACKEND_EXCEPTIONS` below rather than asserted against
// `--vm` output. The tree-walker (oracle) and `--jit` (via VM fallback,
// once #4024 is fixed) still hold this case to the full parity bar.
fn main() {
    let mut x = 0;
    unsafe {
        x = 42;
        println("inside unsafe block");
    }
    println(x);
}
main();
